# Day 02 - Majority Element

## Problem Statement
Given an integer array `nums` of size `n`, return the majority element.

The majority element is the element that appears more than `⌊n / 2⌋` times. It is guaranteed that the majority element always exists in the array.

## Code

class Solution {
public:
    int majorityElement(vector<int>& nums) {
        int freq = 0, ans = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {
            if (freq == 0) {
                ans = nums[i];
            }

            if (ans == nums[i]) {
                freq++;
            } else {
                freq--;
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
};



## Time Complexity
**O(n)**

## Space Complexity
**O(1)**

## Approach
This solution uses the **Boyer-Moore Voting Algorithm**. We maintain a candidate (`ans`) and a counter (`freq`). Initially, when the counter becomes `0`, we select the current element as the new candidate. If the current element matches the candidate, we increment the counter; otherwise, we decrement it. Since the majority element appears more than `n/2` times, it cannot be completely canceled out by the other elements. Therefore, after traversing the array once, the remaining candidate is guaranteed to be the majority element.
